support!

 Adobe MAX: We met so many of you! 

What an incredible experience! We went to Adobe MAX as a sponsor
and had an absolute blast meeting our users, introducing FireCut
to new editors, and connecting with so many of our amazing
affiliates. We hope you're enjoying your FireCut swag. 


Genuinely, thank you again for all your support along the FireCut
journey! We wouldn't be sharing FireCut at one of the biggest
creativity conferences without your support and feedback. 

---------------
FireCut Updates
---------------


FireCut for DaVinci Resolve

November brought some of our biggest updates yet! 

*  Animated Captions* New color picker
* Portrait orientation (9:16)
* Text gradients
* New presets
* Font previews
* Captions history and target video track

*  Languages* Translate captions into 50+ languages
* Voice Activity Detection strips away silent parts across
Captions, Chapters, Zooms, Highlights, Multitrack, and B-roll
transcription to improve AI accuracy (can be disabled)
* Highlights & Multitrack now respect the default audio language

*  Zooms* Improved panel with better scope (full sequence vs.
in/out points) selector and zoom area selection

*  Stills* We have added stills (screenshots of your timeline
at the current position) to add zooms, captions, and create
highlights

*  Bug fixes

... with improvements and more features coming every week.

We’ve written about the https://click.e.economist.com/?qs=3a0b2e8e95c9e6417089a0177b1e73180d57dd25936477d29d646e8ec186903b171a7f48ae6f61ae7bf79da54709568bc0dc4b6c1ef90c15 growing political gulf between young men and women, for example, and the https://click.e.economist.com/?qs=3a0b2e8e95c9e641b8b8fbb2178fd8b6fa7accf1d219c5ec2d1235be639994cbd8d0c3586aeb46620545c20eb88bcef486e0b4eb6794749a stunning decline in the preference for boy babies around the world. This week our cover in most of the world tackles the great relationship recession. Across the rich world, more and more people are coupling up later in life or not at all. The share of 25-34-year-olds in America who are single has doubled in the past five decades. In 26 out of 30 OECD countries more people are living alone than in the past. For some https://click.e.economist.com/?qs=3a0b2e8e95c9e64179a2da7fb31efaf23c2b19b1d69a86d2c0ea2aeb1e8d74b26d79874543c1d86f979739475609c39f50bb519dfa87282a conservative pro-natalists , the failure of young people to settle down and procreate threatens to end Western civilisation. https://click.e.economist.com/?qs=3a0b2e8e95c9e641ffb562dc3706b3e4867eb387f5ff3b11e67ea133214cf9c9fe7bab252e797cf9a3352788553f1575830917c185b38c2d We offer a more nuanced take . The rise of singlehood is largely the result of something good. As barriers to women supporting themselves have fallen, they find it easier to walk out of bad relationships, or to refuse to enter them in the first place. Yet something is amiss in the relationship market. Though many people are happy to fly solo, a hefty majority are not. column7: Breaking Into Data: How to Land Your First Job in a Competitive Market
column9:
View this post on the web at https://seattledataguy.substack.com/p/breaking-into-data-how-to-land-your

If youve been keeping up with the job market, youve probably seen stories about roles receiving hundreds if not thousands of applications within a few days, leaving hiring managers overwhelmed.
So, how do you stand out in such a saturated market?
How do you land a joblet alone your first role in the data world?
I remember facing those same questions and feeling pretty hopeless. I was only six months away from graduating, with no technical work experience beyond teaching kids to code, and had already sent out hundreds of resumes. I managed to land a single interview, but being my first technical interview, I didnt do so hot.
I get how discouraging it can feel just hoping someone will notice your resume and give you a chance.
If youre starting your job search or are about to finish school, I want to share some tactical tips and personal insights to help you break into the data industry [ https://substack.com/redirect/5df328a5-d14f-465a-ac09-8bd69591fd6b?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
SeattleDataGuys Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
1) Dont Get Distracted By Job Titles, Remote Jobs or By Companies
When I was job hunting the second time around, I didnt even know data engineer was a job title. I searched job boards by skill sets insteadthings I knew I had done before, like automating workflows, using SQL [ https://substack.com/redirect/f3b5ec78-848c-4a08-b5da-49b826e26c23?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], and building tables in a data warehouse. [ https://substack.com/redirect/e37f7d2e-f601-4a71-998b-05e097437506?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Job titles evolve.
What used to be called an ETL Developer might now be labeled Data Engineer [ https://substack.com/redirect/38e6723c-1410-4376-8d9b-5b0f58af1230?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] with more expectations. Roles morph, overlap, and get rebranded all the time. If you get too caught up in chasing a specific title, you could miss great opportunities that match your skills.
The same goes for companies. Like many in Seattle, I was laser-focused on landing a job in big tech, especially since, at the time, Amazon was basically spamming job boards. Every other job was at Amazon.
But heres the thingthere are plenty of options:
Startups
Smaller companies
Healthcare organizations
Local companies in general
To name a few.
These companies often have fewer applicants and equally challenging problems to solve. So, while applying for big tech jobs can be part of your plan (if thats your goal), dont limit yourself.
Your first job doesnt have to be flashy with a salary in the 99th percentile right out of the gateit just needs to be a place where you can grow and learn.
2) If You Fail To Prepare, Youd Better Prepare To Fail
What should I study for my interview in two days?"
I get messages like this all the timewhether during live sessions or in my YouTube [ https://substack.com/redirect/75d049f9-70fb-4f1d-b13f-2abb460b0de3?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] comments. Honestly, it stresses me out for those frantically cramming. I can only hope theyre asking for last-minute topics, not just starting to prepare.
Technical interviews [ https://substack.com/redirect/66d57aec-602b-46a5-a173-df092323f1f1?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] are tough. They typically cover a mix of programming, SQL, system design, statistics, and more. The last thing you want is to panic-study a dozen topics. But its also easy to feel overwhelmed by everything you can review. Heres how to focus your efforts effectively:
Create a study plan
If youve got an interview, ask your recruiter for topics
Find a group to keep you accountable
Dont wait until the last minute to study. While some interviews might dive into role-specific technologies, most data-related interviews will test your SQL skills and often include light programming challenges. Preparing in advance ensures youre ready for these core topics and can focus on areas that matter most.
Remember, youve worked hard to get this interview opportunityitd be a shame for you to lose it because you didnt start preparing until the interview date was set.
If youre looking for interview guides, here are a few you can use:
Data Engineer Interview Guide [ https://substack.com/redirect/f82c7c3d-3c20-4b45-a108-ea706c79cbc2?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Data Science Interview Guide [ https://substack.com/redirect/6dbe554c-0482-4af4-a10f-18b53107e60e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
3) Relationships And Referrals
As the world leans further into AI, genuine, in-person relationships are becoming more critical. Our inboxes are overflowing with spam emails from B2B SaaS salespeople, and the constant noise online can make meaningful connections feel rare. Because of this, reverting back to more personal, face-to-face relationships seems inevitable.
I've already had multiple hiring managers reach out to me for referrals after trying the traditional route of posting job listings. They received so many resumes that sorting through them all became challenging. Instead, they turned to their networks, seeking recommendations from people they trusted outside their companies.
So, how can you start building up your own network and professional relationships? Heres where you should begin:
Attend Data Events in Your Area: Check platforms like Meet-up.com or ask industry peers about events they recommend. Ive made a lot of connections through going to different meet-ups and events. I would recommend you dont go in with the mind set that the people you are talking to owe you a job. It often can feel transactional to the people on the other side. 
Reconnect With Classmates: The mistake most people make when it comes to networking [ https://substack.com/redirect/925a1628-b746-483d-b8ad-06e86d7ef0b2?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] is they only reach out when you need something. So be better! Stay in touch with classmates or past colleagues. Check in on them. Ask them how they are doing, grab coffee, and be genuine. 
Leverage LinkedIn: LinkedIn is more than a place to post about how you just landed a new job. Its also a great place to connect with people. However, simply sending your resume to someone and expecting a job offer wont get you far. In fact, you can probably find several posts on LinkedIn complaining about that kind of behavior. Instead, engage with posts, comment thoughtfully, and share your learning experiences. By being active and authentic, youll make more meaningful connections that can open doors over time.
Participate in Online Communities: There are countless data communities where you can engage with peers and discuss tools like dbt [ https://substack.com/redirect/4dc6e768-3e9d-49f2-bf07-b2d80c2ef436?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], SQLMesh [ https://substack.com/redirect/3661b1f6-b7b0-4f3c-af9b-856d9b73dfac?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] or Airflow [ https://substack.com/redirect/02950b9a-616d-4a70-b974-31c778a6dff5?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], as well as broader topics in data engineering and data science. Join these groups, ask thoughtful questions, share your progress, and contribute where you can. Avoid lurkinggetting involved is how youll build a reputation and professional relationships.
Once you start meeting people, here are a few steps to help solidify and grow those relationships.
Ask Thoughtful Questions: When connecting with new people, show genuine curiosity about their experiences and perspectives. If the only thing you care about is getting a job, it shows. People will likely be turned off.
Follow-Up After Initial Meetings: If you've attended an event or had a conversation, follow up with a brief email or LinkedIn message. Honestly, most people dont do this. Maybe you get busy or are afraid of what theyd think.
Be Intentional About Networking: I find that many people only passively network. They go to an event and meet maybe 1-2 people. Dont get me wrong, your goal shouldnt be to try to talk to everyone. But networking requires effort. You need to try to talk to a more than just one person. So be active at events, talk to people, find out who is managing the event, get to know them, etc.
Say Yes to Opportunities: If someone invites you to an event or introduces you to a new connection, take the opportunity. Expanding your circle often starts with being open to new experiences.
4) Obscurity Is the Enemy
I swear, it feels like everyone needs to be a brand or influencer just to get noticed. Honestly, I dont believe thats truebut I do agree with other writers(see Joe Reis  ) who say obscurity is the real enemy when it comes to advancing your career.
That doesnt mean you have to pump out content constantly (though sharing what youre working on can be a powerful way to build visibility). Instead, here are some effective ways to avoid staying obscure:
Engage onlinejoin different Slack groups, get involved, and be helpful.
Contribute to open source.
Write content and share what youre learning.
Go to events and contribute to conversations.
If youre not consistently doing one or more of these things, you risk losing out to those who are. Personally, I focused on writing and attending eventsI wanted to get involved, learn, and grow.
Need a little extra motivation? Check out Never Eat Alone [ https://substack.com/redirect/3b8eeff8-ad9d-41f2-b746-6929323f8408?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. Yes, its a bit of a cheesy business self-help book, but it does help motivate you to step out of your comfort zone.
At the end of the day, if no one knows you exist and if youre relying solely on job applications, you could be waiting a long time to land your next role. Visibility mattersstart taking steps to get noticed.
Before we dive into the more tactical side of interview prep, Id also like to add a quick tip from my friend Abhishek Gupta [ https://substack.com/redirect/e534459a-6073-43b0-ba77-dc2770118f1b?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] who has landed jobs at Facebook, Lyft and Stripe.
I would say be able to showcase end-to-end projects [ https://substack.com/redirect/db222e9a-9be2-45c0-9295-835d2d656f9f?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. They dont have to be super polished, but if you can talk about how you got data from a source system, to a downstream table, transformed it using airflow, and built something preliminary using superset, then I think the person interviewing would get a lot more confidence.
5) Tactical Steps For Interview Prep
Lets talk tactical stepswhat can you do today, next week, and over the next few months to land a job? Start with the basics:
Make Sure the Basics Are in Order:
Resume [ https://substack.com/redirect/4f7c2672-4a45-4ffd-a426-014cd1d36135?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]: Tailor it for each job, keep it ATS-friendly, and focus on achievements rather than tasks. Have someone you trust review it for clarity and impact. Also, I will say using tools like ChatGPT can help you improve your verb [ https://substack.com/redirect/0e632877-08d1-4e79-97d5-13011be1f08a?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] choice and also point out where your bullets are weak.
Portfolio: If you dont have projects, now is a great time to start putting them together. You dont have to have a fancy portfolio website, but at least put together a Github project and show them off. 
LinkedIn Profile: If you are using LinkedIn to comment, post and engage, make sure you clearly show what your skill sets are. Share Github links, talk about past projects, have a buttoned up profile, etc. 
Track Your Progress: One of the biggest challenges during a job search is staying motivated. Often, the struggle comes from not keeping track of your efforts. I have had conversations with people who think put in a lot of effort but have only put out about 20-30 job applications and havent even gone out of there way to meet new people. I get it, it is a hard market, but you cant expect jobs to just fall into your lap. So ask yourself, how many applications have you actually submitted? How many meet-ups have you attended? Keep track of:
Applications Sent
Meet-ups
People You Meet and Follow-Up With
Study and Prepare:
Create an Interview Checklist: Dont study randomlybuild a checklist [ https://substack.com/redirect/6dbe554c-0482-4af4-a10f-18b53107e60e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] of topics, questions, and resources, marking them off as you go(like the ones provided above).
Mock Interviews: Practice both technical and behavioral questions to build confidence. The best way to do this would be to get a friend who is also technical to interview you. Colleges also often offer options here where you can go to the career center and have someone interview you.
Keep Yourself Accountable:
Set Weekly Goals: Define clear, achievable targets like apply to 10 jobs, reach out to five people, or attend one networking event. Many job seekers say, I am trying to find a job, but without a structured plan, they often fall into the trap of sporadically sending out resumes without consistent effort.
Celebrate Small Wins: Recognize milestones along the waygetting an interview, connecting with a key contact, moving past the first phone interview, or advancing to the technical round. Many people overlook these moments, but each step forward is progress worth acknowledging.
Final Thoughts
Landing a jobespecially your firsthas been tough for a while. I remember when I was trying to break into data, people struggled with similar issues.
Entry-level jobs required 2-3+ years of experience.
ATS filters rejected resumes before a human ever saw them.
The surge of interest in becoming a data scientist saturated the market.
Now, were also competing for remote jobs and facing the added challenge of LLMs churning out thousands of generic resumes. However, challenges will continue to exist and evolve. That doesnt mean you should throw your hands up in defeat. If you have the right skills and you can pass an interview, trust the process.
Focus on building genuine relationships, skills [ https://substack.com/redirect/3d9a4c59-fb00-41c4-a7aa-fcda1b010b87?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], and pushing yourself without losing heart.
Wherever you are in your job-searching journey, pick a few tactical steps from the list above and execute. Right nowfind a meet-up and attend the next event, join a data community, spend time getting to know the space, and when youre ready, start sharing what youre learning.
With that, I want to say thank you for reading.

Incremental Load vs Full Load ETL: Key Differences + Examples
ETL and ELT are two widely used data integration techniques. Both methods involve extracting and consolidating data from multiple sources to a single destination. Many organizations prefer the ETL method: it is more compatible with legacy systems and supports transformations before loading, providing more control over data quality and consistency.
Choosing the right data loading strategy is critical for efficient ETL processing. There are several types of data loading processes, including full refresh, full load, and incremental load.
Here, you will find a detailed comparison of incremental load vs full load. How to tell a story with data
By Torsten Walbaum  and Tessa Xie  
As long as humans have existed, they have told stories. For example, the cave paintings in Lascaux, France, are over 30,000 years old and show traces of early graphical storytelling.
And stories still play a central role in our lives today. Ask yourself:
How much do you remember from the last slide deck you saw at work? Probably not much
But how much do you remember from The Lord of the Rings or The Office [or whatever book / movie you like]? Chances are, you can quote entire scenes
If you want to get your point across and make a lasting impression, you need to wrap it in a narrative. Sometimes, people who work with data think theyre an exception to this. Data represents cold, hard facts  that should be convincing enough, no?

column7: Thank You for 100k: A Journey Through 2024 and Beyond
column9:
View this post on the web at https://seattledataguy.substack.com/p/thank-you-for-100k-a-journey-through

2024 is either already over or about to be, depending on where you live, and I wanted to put out one final newsletter.
One of the things I enjoy doing is at the end of the year reviewing the work I have been doing under the Seattle Data Guy umbrella. So, in this article, we will be reviewing the client trends I have seen, highlighting some of the top pieces of content I have put out, as well as discussing some of the new goals for 2025.
Its actually beneficial because I looked back at my 2023 SDG review, and I realized I totally forgot about running data dinners.
So lets talk about content, consulting, and what you can expect in 2025 from the Seattle Data Guy!
But before doing that!
Thank You For 100k!
I just wanted to start by saying thank you to all my readers, subscribers, and YouTube viewers. In 2024 I crossed 100k subscribers both on Youtube [ https://substack.com/redirect/df9426d2-24d8-497c-aa00-a33e5c9825db?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] and Substack. I really appreciate all your support.
The fact that so many people read, like, share, watch, and subscribe really means a lot. I really want to double down on content next year, so I hope to provide even more value to SDG readers and watchers. 
By The Numbers
Speaking of numbers, here are a few more that Id like to share with yall of some personal accomplishments.
I wrote 70+ articles and newsletters, both here and on the Seattle Data Guy website [ https://substack.com/redirect/6723bf05-2868-4db2-83c7-8b4f9b401feb?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
Grew a technical consulting community [ https://substack.com/redirect/944f16df-1cd7-4585-835c-4e0a5c7f0b7b?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] to over +1400 members!
Filmed 28 videos and 35 lives
Held one virtual conferences with over 4500 people signing up(You can find the videos here for the most recent one here [ https://substack.com/redirect/0e6612bd-082e-4fd2-a81c-faad5e65311d?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ])
Landed well over a dozen different projects(ranging from greenfield data stacks and migrations to product analysis)
But enough metrics.
Lets review everything from the type of client work I did to the most popular articles and videos I put out. Well cover:
Project Trends - I will review the types of projects I took on because theyll provide some insight into what is going on in the data world.
Most Popular Articles - There are so many articles that I put out this year that I wanted to go over just a handful that yall really enjoyed.
Most Popular Videos - In many of my newsletters, I will share a video from the Seattle Data Guy YouTube channel. Here are some of the most popular from 2024.
Conference - This was the second year I co-ran the Data Engineering and Machine Learning Summit. So, I wanted to share some of the talks linked below!
Advising - Over the past year, I have found myself advising more about products, and I wanted to share some of their recent feature releases.
1. Project Trends
SQL Server And On-Prem Migrations - This year I had multiple SQL Server migrations [ https://substack.com/redirect/8a5b07fe-e32b-4de8-af37-b849e608949d?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] to cloud data warehouses. Actually, this has been a theme for the last two years but Id say it really peaked this year(or maybe its just a false peak). I also noticed another trend that would happen post migration. Which is the next one below.
Increasing Data Sources - Every company would migrate, then theyd be surprised how easy itd be to pull in even more data sets as they could worry less in terms of compute and storage in turn theyd end up increasing the amount of data sources being pulled into the data warehouse [ https://substack.com/redirect/f2827c62-0f5d-41dd-a29e-6550749e8507?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] and gain new insights. 
Fractional Data Teams - I had a few projects this year where the company had a data team in the past, but moving forward, they wanted some level of fractional data team or specialist instead. These projects, in particular, involved smaller companies that had data teams with 2-5 people on them originally. However, wanted to see if they could do more with less.
Consolidation In Tooling - There were several projects this year where the goal was to reduce the amount of tools being used. Either when building the data stack or minimizing the current one.
2. Popular Articles
In 2024, I really made an effort to put out at least four newsletters a month with some form of graphic. I actually kept this up this year and even had a few months when I put out five newsletters.
Here are some of the ones you engaged with the most!
 Don't Lead a Data Team Before Reading This [ https://substack.com/redirect/9535a6a4-88f0-44e6-9278-bbdaa376e352?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] - I wrote this article because I had recently chatted with 2-to 3 data leaders who say that the default state of most data teams is a failure. But I don't think most data teams are set up for success to start with(I also don't believe that failure is the default state). So, I wrote this article to help new data leaders get a better understanding of how they can lead their teams to success.
Data Warehousing Essentials: A Precursor [ https://substack.com/redirect/aed0f98d-3292-470a-8a3d-f01a577a8dac?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] - If you're looking for a basic rundown of data warehousing, then here it is. In this article, I'll go through some of the basics in terms of dimensional modeling as well as discuss an example of a common data modeling decision you often have to make.
Behind the Scenes of SQL: Understanding SQL Query Execution [ https://substack.com/redirect/2e91e496-0f7b-41e3-821d-9db1d247af64?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] - How does SQL go from English into the lingua franca of data? What happens behind the scenes? Let's dig into it in this article.
Thinking Like an Owner: Elevating Your Data Team's Impact In 2025 [ https://substack.com/redirect/1847ecb2-4f25-49a6-9b8b-eff3bfa4a697?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] - It can be tempting as an IC to sit back and let your director or other teams dictate the work that you take on. But the truth is, most people I've talked to, whether it be directors or high-level ICs, somehow had to push to get the work that they wanted to grow in their careers [ https://substack.com/redirect/9cd021c4-48b3-4963-91b2-9141c7bde86d?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. So, let's talk about how you can take ownership of your career and projects!
Data Engineering 100-Day Crash Course [ https://substack.com/redirect/734b7ad5-af7e-419a-ba66-f8a88379be44?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] - It can be challenging to break into data engineering directly. There seems to be a need to learn a whole plethora of skills that range from programming to data modeling. Perhaps that's why I often see a lot of individuals moving laterally into data engineering; many people go from data analyst to data engineer. Here is a 100-day crash course to get you started on your data engineering journey.
My favorite article from 2024:
 Beyond Big Tech: The Reality Of Data Engineering Outside Silicon Valley [ https://substack.com/redirect/e05ea065-3b8c-4ffc-a8e7-45491a52d358?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] - This was one of my favorite articles. I think it can be easy to feel like everyone else is using the newest technologies and working on hard data problems. But depending on where you work and what team you're working on, it can drastically impact your data stack. So, let's review what other data stacks look like outside of the Bay.
As Christmas has just passed us and the New Year is about to start I wanted to offer all my readers a special gift! If you use the code below youll get 55% off of my newsletter forever!
3. Some Of My Favorite Videos
Video, in general, hasn't been my main focus over the past two years as I have been writing more and had plenty of work on the consulting side. But I still managed to put out a decent amount of videos!
Here are just a few of my favorites.
Going From Data Engineer To Head Of Data - How To Run A Data Team Successfully [ https://substack.com/redirect/a8f4ab35-d558-48e9-947d-cdfd3b9a6477?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
How And Why Data Engineers Need To Care About Data Quality Now - And How To Implement It [ https://substack.com/redirect/20f194a4-2fb3-4204-bea2-2b78fb354bba?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Using AWS Lambda As A Data Engineering - Automating An API Extract With AWS Lambda And Eventbridge [ https://substack.com/redirect/309d15c6-e128-411d-ab0a-bd2b6a1b45d6?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Data Modeling Where Theory Meets Reality - How Different Companies I Worked At Modeled Their Data [ https://substack.com/redirect/3e7607f3-3595-45ee-ac8c-dbc071bb5d55?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Snowflake vs Databricks - And the Battle For Iceberg [ https://substack.com/redirect/a3b77288-6425-4175-b299-e8af370f4096?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
SeattleDataGuys Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
4. Conference
Along with all of the consulting and advising, I co-ran the DEML(Data Engineering And Machine Learning Summit) again this year. We had well over 4500+ sign up. We also set up a separate Youtube channel for the content, so its easy to get to! So check out some of the videos below!
Multimodal RAG with Bedrock [ https://substack.com/redirect/866645f8-b18b-4b2e-805b-a46aaacdfdae?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
All about Iceberg and its Catalogs - What Is Apache Iceberg [ https://substack.com/redirect/1cc6be4c-91ab-46a8-a94e-a6c9f39dd381?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Data Management for LLMs [ https://substack.com/redirect/1c0dec03-142b-4dcd-a668-a41fc5728729?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Innovate and Lead Strategies for Success with Next Gen Data Stack [ https://substack.com/redirect/bc607a1c-28bb-4715-b8ac-cd76ef31b597?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Event Tracking Redefined A Data Engineer's Guide to Creating Actionable Insights [ https://substack.com/redirect/c89d738a-712a-4965-a38f-f17217dfd237?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
5. Advisory
Last year, I put the advisory and conferences under one heading. However, I found that this year, advising took up more of my time. Which I find awesome.
What I have really enjoyed about advising is it lets me be involved in projects and products that are bigger than my one-person operation. Its also great to see how much these companies have put out in terms of features in the last year.
Here are a few highlights from working with them.
Estuary [ https://substack.com/redirect/02fca9ce-bfa7-40f6-9e83-4f61a6e86020?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Towards the latter half of this year, Estuary was on a tear of partnerships and feature releases. For one, they released their Private Deployments [ https://substack.com/redirect/0ef3950c-8fe8-4c7a-aaf4-c9a2c5163d0e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. This means you can host Estuarys data plan inside of your cloud. They also partnered with several other solutions and service providers like StarTree [ https://substack.com/redirect/d8fcdd26-9a05-4b37-ae52-9a8b2757e75e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], Outlier Data [ https://substack.com/redirect/9c1f83b5-3946-43ae-b1d6-92ba4bfc3706?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], and more [ https://substack.com/redirect/a51e5799-f12e-47b9-a99e-5225ec04febb?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]! 
Mage [ https://substack.com/redirect/cb361e69-cc33-44c8-804a-86b9399a3d4c?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
If you missed it, Mage has been releasing a lot of great features as well, including dynamic blocks [ https://substack.com/redirect/564b063c-a0b4-4fae-935e-3285aad5e4ee?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] and also Mage Pro! [ https://substack.com/redirect/d4578a2e-8153-4935-94ab-40a78e990fed?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] Its been awesome to see the community around Mage grow as well as the team get involved with communities such as the DataTalksClub [ https://substack.com/redirect/4ad4f03c-c27d-49b4-92e3-f0a1c5f10257?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] who hosts the DE Zoom Camp [ https://substack.com/redirect/03ef436b-7d93-4d12-8012-bb54b1e50ad2?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
Roe AI [ https://substack.com/redirect/7cedaf22-9369-47f3-b0d5-9779ae2fc9c9?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] 
I just started working with Roe, but its fantastic to hear about the projects they are taking on. If youre trying to analyze PDFs or unstructured data, you should schedule some time with Richard and Jason [ https://substack.com/redirect/bde804d1-3c8b-49c4-8a0d-5ac28756d63d?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
Seattle Data Guy In 2025
Once again, thank you to all my readers and subscribers. Your reading, sharing, and liking of any of my content means the world to me. As someone who has been putting out content online for 7-8 years, it keeps me excited to write more!
Now, looking towards 2025, here are just some of the things you can expect, but let me know if you have topics or events you think I should put together!
Finishing My Book On Data LeadershipTowards the end of this year, I started putting together a book on leading data teams [ https://substack.com/redirect/af41deab-aa6e-44bb-8d1e-21bdbd9b2f04?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. I had a conversation with several CEOs who were talking about the challenges they faced with their data leadership. In my experience, many data leaders get thrown into leading data teams with no real training. So, sure, you can complain about how they might be leading, but I do think we could do a better job preparing them.
Put Out Webinars and Mini-Courses Specifically For The NewsletterI am already starting to film and plan some mini-courses and webinars for paid newsletter members. My goal will be to provide even more in-depth content on topics ranging from how to set up your data infrastructure to running data projects.
Data DinnersLooking back, this has been on my list since 2022, and I still havent done it. Perhaps this is one of those ideas that will never happen, but I am going to try it one more time! Id like to put together dinners for data leaders to provide them with a space to share and grow with others.
Technical Freelancer CommunityIn 2025, I really want to double down on two things: data leadership content and content for technical consultants. Much of that content will be on the TFA Community [ https://substack.com/redirect/ae391bf2-3c56-4fdc-847a-fd855fa961c7?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. I hope to grow the group to 10,000 members by 2026 by creating a space where people can ask questions and find helpful content on their consulting journey.
Spend Less Time In Front Of A KeyboardThis goal will conflict with some of the ones mentioned above. But I do feel like I might spend a little too much time typing away at my keyboard.

Unsubscribe https://substack.com/redirect/2/eyJlIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9zZWF0dGxlZGF0YWd1eS5zdWJzdGFjay5jb20vYWN0aW9uL2Rpc2FibGVfZW1haWw_.PomQKuqTjI4iXEgCRNDfwHGxlz8kSXNBe9hOK3hAZVc?

column7: 5 Hard-Earned Lessons in Building a Successful Data Career: Embracing Mistakes and Driving Impact
column9:
View this post on the web at https://seattledataguy.substack.com/p/5-hard-earned-lessons-in-building

Some lessons can be learned by reading books and building projects. Others? You have to learn the hard waythrough mistakes, trial and error, and sometimes repeating the same missteps over and over until they finally stick.
This is especially true in technical roles, where youre constantly juggling both hard and soft skills. Learning both at once isnt easy. In my own career, Ive found that certain moments stand outusually when life slows down just enough for me to reflect on whats working, what isnt, and how I can improve.
So, in this article, I want to share some of the lessons Ive learned the hard waywhether through embarrassing mistakes, challenging experiences, or simply time passing. Hopefully, theyll save you some trouble along the way.
1) Dont Bury the Lede
If youre part of my Data Leaders Community, you might have attended a recent webinar [ https://substack.com/redirect/a66c75c1-7b41-45bb-836f-4e497ab6591b?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] where Tessa Xie  shared useful frameworks for data leaders. One of them was the Minto Pyramid [ https://substack.com/redirect/33cbfdd9-1117-4c21-9c11-8e517e7c7bba?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], a communication framework that emphasizes leading with the key message before diving into supporting details.
Many of us technical folk tend to do the opposite. We start by explaining our analysis:
We considered choices X and Y, explored these supporting factors, and ultimately decided to go with X.
Vs.
Were going with X after considering X and Y. 
Stakeholders, especially executives, dont need a full breakdown before they hear the conclusion. They want to know what youre doing to fix the problemthen, if necessary, the why.
We tend to bury the lede. Maybe its because we want to showcase all the work we did, or maybe because were trying to soften the blow of bad news. Either way, whether youre presenting a recommendation or sharing tough news, get to the point quickly.
SeattleDataGuys Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
2) Get to Know the People You Work WithAnd What They Care About
Ive talked a lot about communicating [ https://substack.com/redirect/786732d4-e59d-4679-bb62-c216bc6941bd?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] with the business in relevant language. Another way to look at this is to get to know the people you work with and understand what actually matters to them.
What pains are they facing?
What values drive their decisions?
What goals are they trying to achieve?
As data leaders and engineers, its easy to focus solely on the workon writing queries, optimizing pipelines [ https://substack.com/redirect/fd85377d-f73f-4f07-9e79-35dc77ce34d6?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], and keeping things running. Its easy to assume that as long as were delivering results, were doing our job well.
But heres the thing: people dont just want solutions(well specifically not solutions they didnt ask for)they want to feel heard. If we take the time to truly understand the problems others are trying to solve, were not just making their lives easierwere making our work more impactful.
Because we are building what they need.
That starts with good questions:
How do you see our customers needs evolving, and what trends are most critical to you?
What are the biggest uncertainties in our operations, and how can data help clarify them?
How do you currently measure success across your teams?
The truth is, many of us are just waiting for our turn to talk instead of actively listening. The real value comes when we shift from simply executing tasks to solving real problems in ways that matter to the business.
3) Have Opinions And Be Willing To Commit
I once read an article that suggested that you should be easy to work with if you want people to like you. 
And its true, but also
You do need to push back sometimes and have opinions. Yes, you want to be a team player. You dont want to be the person who shoots down every suggestion just to prove a pointno one enjoys working with that person.
But at the same time, you dont want to be so indecisive that every new opinion sways you. Early in my career, I made that mistake. I was working on a project where we were defining the technology stack, and on a call, I let a single comment from another engineer make our entire plan sound less solid. The stakeholder picked up on my hesitation immediatelyand they werent happy about it.
Ill be honest: in a lot of conversations, being a little wobbly in my convictions didnt have much impact. But in high-stakes discussions, that hesitation can be a problem.
The tricky thing is that conviction is a skill you have to practice, even in low-stakes situations, so that when it really matters, youre ready. Youre not always shooting the shit, so to speakyou have to be ready to stand by your principles.
"Disagree and commit" [ https://substack.com/redirect/28988856-c4c0-4067-96a0-c6c9754802a5?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
So, what does this look like in practice?
If you disagree with an idea, dont just dismiss itoffer a better alternative.
Proactively [ https://substack.com/redirect/544fa6a3-6105-4ce9-a2bf-0215d440fdf3?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] identify problems and suggest solutions that make sense for the company.
Go to meetings prepared, having already thought through possible approaches.
In short, be easy to work with, but dont be a pushover. The more senior you become, the more youre expected to push back when ideas arent great.
4) Learn To Tell Stories With Data
At the end of the day, data isnt just about numbers. If you can make data work for you by framing it within a compelling story, youll get people excited about taking action. Even when youre delivering bad news, pairing it with hope and a clear path forward gives people something to rally behind.
Telling effective data stories requires many of the same skills weve already discussed:
Understanding your audienceWhat do they care about? What language resonates with them?
Clarifying your goalWhat action do you want people to take after hearing your insights?
Focusing on impact [ https://substack.com/redirect/1bc088da-7126-4d5b-b15f-bcb0ea5d4224?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]How does this data improve the company, a process, or a decision?
Sometimes, youll have to share tough news. But just because the news is bad doesnt mean your message has to be. If you come prepared with insights and potential solutions, people will be more willing to listen.
5) Take the Time to Improve Others
Early in my career, I didnt have anyone reviewing my code. That made it difficult to assess whether I was doing well or completely off track. Eventually, I worked at a company with a structured code review and mentoring process, and it was a game changer.
Code reviews, design discussion, and general mentoringthese arent just routine processes. Theyre opportunities to help others grow. Newer engineers learn by seeing how senior engineers approach problems, removing ambiguity from the equation. Instead of wondering, Whats the right way to do this? they get real-world examples of best practices.
Another way to help others improve themselves is by raising the bar. To be clear, I dont mean going around nitpicking every piece of code you see. But theres value in having someone who can push their team to grow.
Its easy for code bases to slip into disrepair. One poorly formatted line of code here, another shortcut thereand suddenly, youre in a broken-window-theory situation, but in your code base.
So, how do you avoid this?
Be the standard. Instead of calling out every mistake, lead by example. Write clean, thoughtful code without needing to be asked.
Challenge people when they fall below it. If you see a teammate breaking away from the standard, dont just point it outhelp them understand why something should be done differently. Its not about enforcing arbitrary rules (the debate over tabs vs. spaces can stay on Reddit) but about guiding people toward better solutions. Tell them why.
The challenge here is that we can get so focused on improving ourselves that we sometimes forget to invest in others. But taking the time to do so makes your team betterand, in the long run, makes your job easier. Win-win.
Challenges You Will Face
Ive mentioned this in past articles, but its worth repeatingnot every company or leader you work for will be perfect, and not everyone actually wants to hear the truth.
Plenty of organizations like the idea of being data-driven. Fewer are willing to invest in what it actually takes to get there.
In some cases, you can bring people around and help them see the light (actually, that will have to be one of my next articles). Other times, youll hit a wall. And when that happens, youll have to decide how to deal with it.
Here are some of the challenges youll likely encounter:
Overcoming resistance to change
Prioritizing initiatives with limited resources
Dealing with ambiguity
Managing up and down
Building and maintaining trust [ https://substack.com/redirect/8e9d8da8-e6c7-416f-8f74-2f24e5a2cd2e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Avoiding burnoutfor yourself and your team [ https://substack.com/redirect/011cde01-0363-4ba3-90ae-012e5ef129bf?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Etc..
And honestly? These arent just challenges for data leaders. Most leaders face these in one way or another.
Final Thoughts
You can read all the books you want, but many lessons are hard to fully grasp until youve actually experienced going through situations. 
Even then, you might make the wrong call a few times before you start to learn. That was a point brought up by Aaron Wilkerson  in a recent live [ https://substack.com/redirect/19e1d50c-2a88-4052-84f5-869a1a37de56?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] I ran a few days back.
So whether youre learning lessons the hard way or through reading, I do wish you the best of luck and as always, thanks for reading!

column7: How To Turn Around A Failing Data Team
column9:
View this post on the web at https://seattledataguy.substack.com/p/how-to-turn-around-a-failing-data

A few years ago, I heard the same observation from several data and business leaders.
The default state of data teams is failure.
This was in the early 2020s, when many data teams felt like they had ballooned in size. Everyone wanted to be data-driven and cheap money made it easy.
Fast-forward to 2025 and the landscape looks very different. Companies are running leaner. Many have intentionally shrunk their data teams and, in some cases, lean more on external partners instead of adding headcount.
As a consultant, Im often brought in when a previous team has disbanded or when leadership wants to turn around a struggling data environment. Across these engagements, Ive seen recurring patterns, root causes that explain why some data stacks and teams fail to deliver, and what it really takes to bring them back on track.
This is based off of my talk at Big Data London.
Root Causes of Data Team Failure
There are many challenges data teams and leaders face. But its not just about picking the wrong technology. Many data leaders find themselves leading data teams with minimal coaching after being an IC [ https://substack.com/redirect/dcbd169d-bf5d-462d-945d-368ef47a2536?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. Others get pulled into being a catch all team where they have to manage not only the reporting but automated processes that might be better suited for a different team while also having to figure out how to lead AI initiatives for their companies.
All that said, here are some common causes of data teams failing.
Lack Of Ownership 
Lack of ownership  can show up in many forms. I liked the way it was described by Alex Ewerlf   in his article 6 Archetypes of Broken Ownership [ https://substack.com/redirect/008c2f3b-d84e-468e-866f-fdbe1577651a?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. In which he references that ownership depends on three elements: mandate, knowledge, and responsibility. If any one of these is missing, true ownership breaks down.
Consider a leader who has the power to make a decision (mandate) but lacks deep understanding (knowledge) and isnt accountable for the consequences (responsibility). They make a call without consulting the team.
The result?
The team delivers the project but morale sinks
People stop raising concerns because they feel their input doesnt matter
Attrition follows as talented engineers look for healthier environments
Other ownership gaps signs:
Key assets, tables, dashboards, critical scripts, become orphaned when the original owner leaves
Technical leads are responsible for data pipelines [ https://substack.com/redirect/13f3c1a2-5a2b-47b0-b7fb-30b454eb48fb?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] but cant influence upstream data quality [ https://substack.com/redirect/8c0d739e-9251-4a50-98ca-74b9746df98a?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Analysts are tasked with metric definitions but cant enforce consistent usage across departments
The truth is, like many things, lack of ownership by itself doesnt usually cause a data team to fail. Instead, its the build-up of multiple issues.
SeattleDataGuys Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
Over-engineering And Wrong Sizing
I view this as a spectrum. Where you can either over-engineer and be burdened by infrastructure that is too complex for the problems you are trying to solve and on the other side have infrastructure that doesnt scale well forcing you to fight fires and deal with technical friction.
In both cases you often lose the ability to cycle quickly through iterations. Instead of experimenting, measuring, and improving, the team is stuck fixing infrastructure, whether thats debugging an overbuilt DAG dependency maze or scrambling to scale a single-node warehouse that keeps running out of credits.
Common over-engineering signs
Chasing the cool tool [ https://substack.com/redirect/9dbb9991-d4df-4539-90c1-55a0ac709dc4?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] of the moment without a clear business requirement
Layering every emerging pattern (micro-services, event buses, lakehouse-plus-warehouse) before proving the need
Designing for hypothetical petabyte scale when current data volumes are modest
Common wrong-sizing(and messy prototyping) signs
Under-estimating data growth and user demand, causing constant outages or painful migrations
Skipping basic reliability features to move fast, which later slows everything down
Leaning on brittle quick fixes, one giant ETL [ https://substack.com/redirect/9d07bb4d-746f-4d97-a3f6-d96072f2c12f?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] script, a single overworked cluster, until making even a small change takes weeks
Both extremes carry the same cost, slower cycle times. Engineers spend their time nursing the platform instead of delivering new insights or helping the business adapt. Making small changes takes forever, even when all you need to do is add a few columns to a table.
Metrics Theater
This is one particularly frustrating because it often appears that the data team [ https://substack.com/redirect/1ef5d58f-2976-490c-b08e-58f6354fdac5?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] has done everything right. Youve built reliable dashboards and a rock-solid analytics platform, yet no one is making real decisions based on the data.
Leaders may even review the numbers weekly or monthly. When metrics are positive, they celebrate. When theyre negative, they shrug: nothing we could have done.
Its all an act. Metrics theater allows leadership to look data-driven without actually being data-driven.
Typical signs:
Everyone says were data-driven, but key calls still come from gut instinct
Metrics are highlighted when favorable and quietly ignored when unfavorable
Reports are created and placed into slide decks, but the business is still facing the same issues
The result is expensive infrastructure and beautiful dashboards that fail to change how the business operates. If thats the case, then the business is really just paying for an expensive paper weight. 
Outputs Without Outcomes
Plenty of companies out there invest millions into their data stack. They build dozens if not hundreds of tables and pipelines, and focus on developing more and more.
Success is measured by what the team ships, not by what the business achieves. Although this is often more implicit. It might not be said, but what gets rewarded is output.
Typical signs:
Number of dashboards, tables, or lines of code lead to promotions
Launching data products that are rarely, if ever, used
Spending millions on migrations or new tooling with no measurable lift in revenue, efficiency, or customer experience
Ive seen teams build 100+ dashboards and complete multiple costly migrations, only to discover that decision-makers barely glance at the outputs.
Both metrics theater and output-focused thinking miss the point. Its a lot of motion without really any true purpose. 
Turning the Ship Around - Your Data Team Turnaround Playbook
But thats enough talking about problems.
Lets go through how you can start to turn your data team around.
Diagnose & Stabilize
Before actually really diving deep youre going to want to pause and just assess what is going on. You need to understand what are the crucial workflows you cant break because they will impact the business? And youll want to see if there are opportunities to simplify but you can only do that by understanding the bigger picture. 
Map the current stack and data flows - Document pipelines, source system, and dependency. There will always be some hidden cron job or Snowflake task  [ https://substack.com/redirect/6fc2a023-5b82-43cd-aefd-7ddfc1e16b6d?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]that you didnt expect that somehow manages the way your business makes money.
Identify must-keep-lights-on processes - Isolate the handful of jobs that keep revenue reporting, billing, or critical dashboards alive. In many cases data teams might be responsible for business critical workflows, you cant mess those up.
Deliver quick wins
Fix broken daily jobs and remove dead code
Standardize naming for tables so everyone can find and use data more easily(specifically target the tables that are heavily used)
Set up simple alerts and monitoring to prevent recurring outages
These early actions buy credibility with leadership and create breathing room for deeper fixes.
Reset Vision & Priorities
Once youve got a good idea and handle of the current data infrastructure its time to reset. You need to be clear of what your teams priorities are and what the vision for your team is in the future. 
What are the 2-3 pillars you believe your data team should focus on?
Do you view it as purely a reporting team? a team that will help integrate data into the product, etc. 
Be clear about it, or youll always end up a catch-all IT/Data/Finance team hybrid.
Reconnect data work to business outcomes - Identify top three to five metrics or use cases the company truly cares about, such as reducing churn, improving conversion, or speeding new product launches.
Publicly prioritize top initiatives with clear owners - Create a short, visible roadmap so the entire company sees what matters and what will not be done.
Get leadership buy-in on stopping low-value work - Make it explicit, ad-hoc requests and nice to have dashboards are paused until the core plan is met. Ok lets be real, most of the ad-hoc workyoull always have to deliver some or people will think youre not willing to help them. But be willing to pushback more or you will never get out of the quagmire. 
Rebuild Foundations
Now you need to rebuild the foundation. And I dont just mean your technical foundation, I mean everything from technical to how you manage ownership, key processes, etc
Establish clear ownership and accountability - Being clear on who and how ownership will work moving forward allows your team to make better decisions because theyll know who is responsible for managing various future artifacts
Simplify architecture and right-size tools - One example I have where I simplified architecture involved 50+ queries supporting a set of dashboards.  I look through them and found they could be consolidated to 3-4 instead. Reducing duplicative code, improving performance and not hitting the data warehouse as often.
Document, automate testing, and enforce standards - This is also a great time to set clear standards on everything from how you test to name tables and columns.
Create an Outcome-Obsessed Culture
Finally, Ive really enjoyed the term outcome-obsessed [ https://substack.com/redirect/ede848d3-d392-4ba7-a91e-0af45106005d?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] recently. Probably because the alliteration. But the point remains, youve got to actually care about what the other side of your project does.
Where the data work stops the business value is just beginning and it doesnt just happen because dashboard exists or a business executive has access to a chatbot.
Define success in business terms, not just technical metrics - Yes, data quality has to be reliable, the dashboards need to load in a reasonable time frame, but the business still has to have a plan for the data.
Bake outcomes into processes - If youre only really starting to think about outcomes after delivering your data products, there is a good change youve already gone down the right path.
Keep communication constant and keep the project going - Just because the data product is delivered doesnt mean you dont have to communicate with anyone in the business anymore. You need to check in, see if they are using the dashboard, see if they have any issues, and so on.
Final Thoughts
Data teams can provide a lot of value for the business but they can also very easily be an expensive paper weight. 
They can find themselves building data pipelines that support dashboards that no one uses and arguing about whether or not they should migrate to Databricks or Snowflake [ https://substack.com/redirect/14806157-fc61-4eab-a8f3-9a76ce3f1591?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] next. 
All while the business is talking about a completely different set of problems and issues that you could be helping on! 
As always, thanks as always for reading!

Articles Worth Reading
There are thousands of new articles posted daily all over the web! I have spent a lot of time sifting through some of these articles as well as TechCrunch and companies tech blog and wanted to share some of my favorites!
Operating Principles That Guided Me to Staff Engineer (Part 2: Expanding Influence)
By Jordan Cutler  
In Part 1 [ https://substack.com/redirect/87640e1d-ac5f-4313-811b-4acdd78fad63?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], Jordan shared the principles that helped him consistently deliver results and reach Staff Engineer. But results dont happen in a vacuum. They depend on the influence you have to make change happen. Influence drives results, and results compound to more influence.
In this part, Jordan will share the guiding principles that helped me build influence to make a multiplicative impact across teams. These principles help you build relationships, strengthen your communication, and be seen as a leader.
Read More Here [ https://substack.com/redirect/4839a493-6722-4cf1-aab5-a1c7d50d103d?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Scaling Muse: How Netflix Powers Data-Driven Creative Insights at Trillion-Row Scale
At Netflix, we prioritize getting timely data and insights into the hands of the people who can act on them. One of our key internal applications for this purpose is Muse. Muses ultimate goal is to help Netflix members discover content theyll love by ensuring our promotional media is as effective and authentic as possible. It achieves this by equipping creative strategists and launch managers with data-driven insights showing which artwork or video clips resonate best with global or regional audiences and flagging outliers such as potentially misleading (clickbait-y) assets. These kinds of applications fall under Online Analytical Processing (OLAP), a category of systems designed for complex querying and data exploration. However, enabling Muse to support new, more advanced filtering and grouping capabilities while maintaining high performance and data accuracy has been a challenge. Previous posts have touched on artwork personalization [ https://substack.com/redirect/901cac2a-03db-4772-8b1b-7cbef8b9a4aa?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] and our impressions architecture [ https://substack.com/redirect/88a3ddee-1b2c-4e0d-a2b4-ae3b3ccb1cff?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. In this post, well discuss some steps weve taken to evolve the Muse data serving layer to enable new capabilities while maintaining high performance and data accuracy.
Read More Here [ https://substack.com/redirect/c75bfc3c-56f7-4681-ac35-a7df14d9f88c?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]

October 1, 2025

Quietly brilliant: Why design at scale is the most fascinating work youll never notice
Quietly brilliant: Why

design at scale is the most

fascinating work youll

never notice


The most interesting design work rarely makes it to the award stage or the Instagram carousel. Its the unglamorous architecture of experiences used by billions: the invisible flows, frameworks, and decisions that keep our most-used tools stable yet adaptable. From Grammarlys growth design team to Google and Landors global systems thinkers, these practitioners show that design at scale isnt about flash, its about shaping ecosystems, nurturing trust, and solving for staggering complexity at a human level.

Also in this issue
* A framework for play: EIGAs modular identity system empowers kindergartens
* Confessions of a conflicted creative: Inside the design industrys regret file
* Check out this week's featured designers!



Beyond the shiny case study: Inside the invisible design shaping billions of daily interactions

Design at scale is often overlooked because it lacks the drama of a big rebrand or a cinematic motion system. Yet its arguably the most consequential work happening today. This story lifts the curtain on the teams quietly shaping tools used by millions, sometimes billions, of people. Grammarlys Verna Swehla compares growth designers to dinnerparty hosts orchestrating every detail of the experience (from first click to longterm engagement) so it feels seamless and human.

Googles Hana Tanimura takes inspiration from trees: rooted but flexible, able to bend without breaking. And Landors Teemu Suviala frames it as designing with the world, not just for it. These designers build living systems, not static style guides. These systems adapt across cultures, devices, and accessibility contexts while remaining recognizable and trustworthy. Its slow, collaborative work with enormous stakes, proving that the quietest design can also be the most creative and impactful.

The brand with 500 faces: Inside the identity system designed for play, purpose, and preschoolers

What happens when a brand system is built not to standardize but to empower? For Germanys Katholino network of kindergartens, EIGA created a flexible, heart-centered identity that invites each school to shape its own presence. The design firm created more than 500 logo variations, custom type built for early learning, and plug-and-play tools for non-designers, balancing individuality with cohesion. Its branding designed not just for consistency, but for community, creativity, and the people who use it every day.

>From museum nights to Spotify playlists, recurring briefs test designers not just on originality, but on reinvention. This feature explores how top studios navigate familiar territory with fresh eyes, building creative systems that thrive on repetition without falling into it.

Design, reloaded: How studios stay fresh with repeat projects

Most dsigners love a blank slate, but what happens when the canvas is the same every year? This piece dives into the art of the returning brief, spotlighting studios that master reinvention under constraint. From Form builds a universe of playful nostalgia for Amsterdam Museum Night. Rabbithole evolves LIFI with each edition while anchoring it in brand continuity. STUDIO HERRSTRM turns Spotify playlists into cultural case studies through systemic design.

Across all three, repetition isnt a rut; its a rhythm. Their secret? Clear processes, shared language, and deep trust. When the brief inevitably comes back, great design doesnt repeat, it resonates more deeply.

>From efficiency to imagination: Looking towards the future of design

After years driving operational excellence at Kaiser Permanente, frustration with processonly thinking led one design leader toward a more human (and more forwardlooking) approach.
